allotment
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number:
Definition:1. A piece of Crown land granted to a particular person for a specified purpose. 2. A piece of land: in towns, a building block; in the country an area use for pasture or cultivation.]
Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: 1. Hist. [AND Hist. [Spec.use of allotment allotted portion of land: see OED 4.]
Citations
Date: 10/9/1841
Source: GBPP
Author:
Vol / Page: 130
Edition:
Quote: The memorial [from Mr.Sinclair, Wellington] states that certain town lots ... had been advertised for sale by auction, but that several allotments, comprising some of the most valuable lands in the township, ... had been reserved from such sale ...; that these sections were to be paid for at the average price of half the town sections.
Notes: Villiers and Lefevre Colonial Land and Emigration Office in GBPP 1842 (No.569) 10 Sep 130 [? an allotting : cf LOT]

Date: 10/2/1841
Source: GBPP
Author:
Vol / Page: 131
Edition:
Quote: By the Government advertisement for the sale of town lands at Auckland, it was stated that sections ... would be exposed to sale by auction, but we have since learned that several allotments, comprising some of the most valuable lands in the township, have been reserved fromsuch sale ...; and that these sections are to be paid for, not according to the price ... of the less valuable lots in their vicinity ... but at the average price of half the town sections ...
Notes: D. Sinclair and others, Wellington to Sir George Gipps in GBPP 1842 (No.569) 10 Feb 131 [cf 10 Sep report a. above]

